1
00:00:35,320 --> 00:00:37,595
<i>Voilà! I'm on the road again...</i>

2
00:00:44,400 --> 00:00:45,355
Shit!

3
00:00:46,320 --> 00:00:47,639
<i>Battery depleted.</i>

4
00:01:02,800 --> 00:01:05,360
<i>Thirty years old...</i>
<i>You gotta take stock.</i>

5
00:01:06,560 --> 00:01:08,596
<i>If I look at my life,</i>
<i>it's not impressive.</i>

6
00:01:09,400 --> 00:01:10,628
<i>What've I done?</i>

7
00:01:12,680 --> 00:01:14,875
<i>I was madly in love with one girl.</i>
<i>Martine.</i>

8
00:01:15,240 --> 00:01:16,673
<i>No, that's not it.</i>

9
00:01:17,600 --> 00:01:20,114
<i>Then I was madly in love</i>
<i>with another. Neus.</i>

10
00:01:20,480 --> 00:01:21,356
<i>Okay...</i>

11
00:01:21,720 --> 00:01:23,278
<i>this story's already a big mess.</i>

12
00:01:23,640 --> 00:01:25,278
<i>That's because I'm a mess.</i>

13
00:01:26,360 --> 00:01:27,588
<i>Let me sort things out.</i>

14
00:01:28,200 --> 00:01:30,316
<i>"Writing is sorting out</i>
<i>the mess of life. "</i>

15
00:01:30,680 --> 00:01:33,877
<i>I'm not telling this in order.</i>
<i>Order's a real mess.</i>

16
00:01:35,360 --> 00:01:38,796
<i>So, that's me.</i>
<i>Last month, in Russia, for a wedding.</i>

17
00:01:40,360 --> 00:01:41,793
<i>Those are people I used to know.</i>

18
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:44,797
<i>Okay, here goes.</i>
<i>Five years ago,</i>

19
00:01:45,520 --> 00:01:48,751
<i>I went to Barcelona</i>
<i>to study economics.</i>

20
00:01:49,120 --> 00:01:50,599
<i>I met them all there.</i>

21
00:01:50,920 --> 00:01:52,751
<i>We shared an apartment for a year.</i>

22
00:02:01,840 --> 00:02:05,549
<i>We lost touch, then reconnected</i>
<i>here, in Saint Petersburg.</i>

23
00:02:06,280 --> 00:02:10,193
<i>Because William, that guy,</i>
<i>is marrying a Russian, Natasha.</i>

24
00:02:10,960 --> 00:02:11,870
<i>Her.</i>

25
00:02:15,800 --> 00:02:18,268
<i>A monumental event</i>
<i>is about to take place in my life.</i>

26
00:02:23,680 --> 00:02:25,477
<i>Something really fundamental.</i>

27
00:02:33,040 --> 00:02:35,759
<i>But to explain why</i>
<i>this thing's so fundamental to me,</i>

28
00:02:36,120 --> 00:02:38,031
<i>let's jump back a year.</i>

29
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:27,471
RUSSIAN DOLLS

30
00:04:31,640 --> 00:04:32,629
<i>Voilà! Now, I write.</i>

31
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:34,718
<i>My job is telling stories.</i>

32
00:04:35,520 --> 00:04:38,637
<i>But this woman has heard</i>
<i>some of my best stories.</i>

33
00:04:39,000 --> 00:04:41,434
<i>Mrs. V., my bank officer.</i>

34
00:04:41,800 --> 00:04:43,631
They can't pay me for two months.

35
00:04:44,040 --> 00:04:46,315
But they said...
And this will interest you.

36
00:04:46,680 --> 00:04:49,399
Because I'm like you.
I said,

37
00:04:50,120 --> 00:04:52,031
"That's scandalous! You can't do that.

38
00:04:52,400 --> 00:04:54,709
"France has strict laws
protecting writers."

39
00:04:55,080 --> 00:04:56,957
I was very, very angry.

40
00:04:57,360 --> 00:04:58,793
What is of interest here?

41
00:04:59,280 --> 00:05:00,998
Well, they said,

42
00:05:01,760 --> 00:05:04,513
since they couldn't pay me
in a timely fashion,

43
00:05:04,880 --> 00:05:06,313
when they do pay me,

44
00:05:06,680 --> 00:05:09,717
they'll take a "late penalty"
into account.

45
00:05:10,240 --> 00:05:11,832
Meaning? I don't understand.

46
00:05:13,760 --> 00:05:16,194
Since they're late,
they'll pay me more.

47
00:05:18,520 --> 00:05:19,635
How much more?

48
00:05:20,040 --> 00:05:22,076
I think they said, "Much, much more."

49
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:25,560
<i>So my job is to play a merry tune.</i>

50
00:05:26,080 --> 00:05:29,629
We typically need writers like you
for personalities

51
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:31,911
who are writing their memoirs

52
00:05:32,280 --> 00:05:34,316
and can't put two words together.

53
00:05:34,680 --> 00:05:36,272
Can you do that?

54
00:05:37,240 --> 00:05:38,309
Ghostwriting?

55
00:05:39,280 --> 00:05:40,759
Yes... no... that's...

56
00:05:41,440 --> 00:05:43,158
Sure, I can be a ghostwriter.

57
00:05:43,520 --> 00:05:44,270
I think...

58
00:05:44,640 --> 00:05:46,232
I preferred to work there.

59
00:05:46,600 --> 00:05:48,750
I can ghostwrite for anyone.

60
00:05:50,640 --> 00:05:53,438
I love fiction
when it's connected to reality...

61
00:05:56,520 --> 00:05:58,431
There was a huge amount
of work there...

62
00:06:01,840 --> 00:06:03,558
<i>So that's the job!</i>
Know what I mean?

63
00:06:03,920 --> 00:06:05,990
<i>Now I'm working</i>
<i>all over the place.</i>

64
00:06:06,360 --> 00:06:09,397
Plum has a roundness, a warmth,

65
00:06:09,880 --> 00:06:12,553
a certain femininity, yet elegance...

66
00:06:12,920 --> 00:06:15,115
Some guys like hot dog or freestyle.

67
00:06:15,480 --> 00:06:17,198
So you need different gear.

68
00:06:17,560 --> 00:06:18,993
Hardware's always been reliable.

69
00:06:19,360 --> 00:06:21,078
OS X makes the difference.

70
00:06:21,440 --> 00:06:23,954
- You mean the equipment?
- No, the ride.

71
00:06:24,280 --> 00:06:26,919
It's chic, not la-di-da.
Hip, yet cool.

72
00:06:27,360 --> 00:06:30,557
- For me, you gotta go freestyle.
- That's color!

73
00:06:37,160 --> 00:06:39,071
Doesn't that kill the trees?

74
00:06:42,800 --> 00:06:43,835
So...

75
00:06:44,200 --> 00:06:46,350
Do you trim them several times a year?

76
00:06:47,360 --> 00:06:49,351
- What do you think?
- Yes? No?

77
00:06:49,720 --> 00:06:51,676
I don't know. I have no idea.

78
00:06:52,040 --> 00:06:54,031
Do grapes grow in winter?

79
00:06:54,400 --> 00:06:57,119
You've been busting my balls
for an hour.

80
00:06:57,480 --> 00:07:00,278
I'm a Parisian,
I don't know this plant shit.

81
00:07:01,280 --> 00:07:04,113
I'm like you,
I got a boring shit job.

82
00:07:04,640 --> 00:07:07,598
I don't give a fuck.
If my questions are stupid,

83
00:07:07,960 --> 00:07:09,678
don't answer and I'll take off!

84
00:07:10,040 --> 00:07:11,632
A little on edge, are we?

85
00:07:12,560 --> 00:07:13,879
Sorry. I haven't slept,

86
00:07:14,240 --> 00:07:15,309
I'm having a shitty day.

87
00:07:15,680 --> 00:07:16,999
Yeah, I'm on edge.

88
00:07:17,560 --> 00:07:19,835
- You Parisians!
- Stop! Enough!

89
00:07:20,200 --> 00:07:21,155
Laurent!

90
00:07:22,640 --> 00:07:26,315
Stop! That side's fine.
The façade's clear!

91
00:07:27,320 --> 00:07:29,436
- When's your shit due?
- In two weeks.

92
00:07:29,800 --> 00:07:32,951
<i>People seem to think</i>
<i>I'm good at love stories.</i>

93
00:07:33,320 --> 00:07:37,598
We're doing a special "love series"
by young writers this summer.

94
00:07:37,960 --> 00:07:39,154
Oh, I'd love to.

95
00:07:40,880 --> 00:07:45,271
<i>So it's gone pretty well this year.</i>
<i>I even got a TV script to write.</i>

96
00:07:49,520 --> 00:07:50,794
<i>Sort of the ultimate!</i>

97
00:07:56,080 --> 00:07:58,116
We read your story with great interest.

98
00:07:59,120 --> 00:08:01,998
It has enormous quality,
but a few scenes

99
00:08:02,360 --> 00:08:03,395
did make us flinch.

100
00:08:03,760 --> 00:08:05,273
More than flinch, even.

101
00:08:08,400 --> 00:08:09,276
Scene 57.

102
00:08:10,200 --> 00:08:14,318
Why doesn't John Edward kiss Odile
during the thunderstorm?

103
00:08:14,680 --> 00:08:16,636
Yes, why? We want them to kiss.

104
00:08:17,080 --> 00:08:18,399
I want them to kiss.

105
00:08:18,760 --> 00:08:21,558
I don't know.
I didn't want to be too cliché.

106
00:08:22,760 --> 00:08:26,435
We so expect it, it's more interesting
if they don't kiss.

107
00:08:26,800 --> 00:08:29,997
But why deprive the audience
of that pleasure?

108
00:08:31,760 --> 00:08:33,079
It airs over the holidays.

109
00:08:33,440 --> 00:08:37,115
It's a marvelous gift to our viewers.
Don't be afraid of clichés.

110
00:08:38,240 --> 00:08:39,229
I more than agree.

111
00:08:39,720 --> 00:08:42,234
It's a sequel.
<i>Wooded Bliss</i> was a huge hit.

112
00:08:42,600 --> 00:08:46,513
The audience is clamoring for
<i>Love Passion in Venice.</i> Go for it.

113
00:08:47,120 --> 00:08:51,477
Everyone's dying to see how John Edward
and Odile finally fall in love.

114
00:08:54,960 --> 00:08:56,996
John Edward's handsome,
Odile's beautiful,

115
00:08:57,360 --> 00:09:00,238
they're in Venice,
the most beautiful city in the world!

116
00:09:00,600 --> 00:09:01,999
Let yourself go, Xavier!

117
00:09:02,360 --> 00:09:03,873
We all love postcards.

118
00:09:04,240 --> 00:09:06,674
We all love sunsets.
Why deny us that?

119
00:09:12,280 --> 00:09:13,872
Put them in gondolas!

120
00:09:18,680 --> 00:09:20,511
I must sell Wooded Bliss.

121
00:09:22,000 --> 00:09:23,228
But why, John Edward?

122
00:09:24,960 --> 00:09:25,836
Why?

123
00:09:32,240 --> 00:09:33,309
I'm getting a divorce.

124
00:09:35,040 --> 00:09:36,268
Does your wife know?

125
00:09:38,600 --> 00:09:39,589
Yes.

126
00:09:39,960 --> 00:09:41,313
I've told her everything.

127
00:09:41,680 --> 00:09:42,476
But that's marvelous.

128
00:09:44,560 --> 00:09:45,595
Ridiculous!

129
00:09:46,120 --> 00:09:47,189
<i>Yes, marvelous...</i>

130
00:09:49,520 --> 00:09:51,556
- It's not ridiculous.
- Come on...

131
00:09:52,080 --> 00:09:54,514
You hate love stories.
Lots of people love them.

132
00:09:54,880 --> 00:09:56,233
It's not ridiculous to them.

133
00:09:56,600 --> 00:09:58,033
So, you're doing the sequel?

134
00:09:59,160 --> 00:09:59,956
<i>I love you.</i>

135
00:10:00,320 --> 00:10:01,719
Well, I hope it pays well.

136
00:10:02,240 --> 00:10:04,356
It pays better than my articles.

137
00:10:04,720 --> 00:10:06,312
So it's <i>adios</i> to your book?

138
00:10:06,680 --> 00:10:08,716
I can't do everything at once.

139
00:10:09,080 --> 00:10:10,149
Did you like it, Lucas?

140
00:10:10,520 --> 00:10:11,873
I liked it a lot.

141
00:10:12,440 --> 00:10:14,396
<i>Maybe it's not what I dreamed of.</i>

142
00:10:15,240 --> 00:10:18,073
<i>But it's a stepping-stone.</i>
<i>I'm learning a ton.</i>

143
00:10:20,560 --> 00:10:21,959
But who can that be?

144
00:10:23,040 --> 00:10:24,109
Are you expecting anyone?

145
00:10:27,160 --> 00:10:29,594
<i>I wrote a book,</i> L'Auberge Espagnole,
<i>5 years ago.</i>

146
00:10:29,960 --> 00:10:33,635
<i>I haven't found a publisher,</i>
<i>but I still have hope.</i>

147
00:10:36,080 --> 00:10:37,035
<i>Barbara, what does this mean?</i>

148
00:10:39,040 --> 00:10:40,268
<i>I knew I'd find you here.</i>

149
00:10:42,320 --> 00:10:43,230
<i>So, she's the one!</i>

150
00:10:44,240 --> 00:10:46,913
<i>You disappoint me.</i>
<i>I thought she'd at least be...</i>

151
00:10:51,920 --> 00:10:52,511
Yes.

152
00:10:53,480 --> 00:10:56,916
Yes, who? Yes, what?
Can't you say who you are?

153
00:10:57,280 --> 00:10:59,714
Everyone else does, why can't you?

154
00:11:00,080 --> 00:11:02,230
What do you want me to say?
"It's your mommy?"

155
00:11:02,600 --> 00:11:04,909
Everyone else does.
Why can't you?

156
00:11:06,000 --> 00:11:09,675
Gimme a break!
You want me to be like everyone else.

157
00:11:10,040 --> 00:11:10,790
It's grampa...

158
00:11:11,160 --> 00:11:11,990
Hold on.

159
00:11:12,760 --> 00:11:14,239
I was sure you'd forget.

160
00:11:15,120 --> 00:11:15,791
Hi, it's Martine.

161
00:11:16,160 --> 00:11:17,229
I'm on the other line.

162
00:11:17,600 --> 00:11:18,316
Quick!

163
00:11:18,840 --> 00:11:19,829
Okay, go ahead.

164
00:11:20,200 --> 00:11:22,270
- About tonight...
- Oh, happy birthday.

165
00:11:22,640 --> 00:11:23,959
You didn't forget?

166
00:11:24,320 --> 00:11:25,196
You done?

167
00:11:25,560 --> 00:11:28,358
Mom, hold on. It's Martine.
It's her birthday.

168
00:11:28,720 --> 00:11:31,075
Wish her happy birthday for me.

169
00:11:31,600 --> 00:11:33,318
My mother says, "Happy birthday."

170
00:11:33,680 --> 00:11:35,557
<i>- Tell her "thanks."</i>
- What time tonight?

171
00:11:36,280 --> 00:11:39,158
- He expects you for dinner tonight.
<i>- Hold on, mom. Not you.</i>

172
00:11:39,520 --> 00:11:41,192
I don't know, nine.

173
00:11:41,560 --> 00:11:42,549
That works.

174
00:11:42,960 --> 00:11:43,870
I gotta go.

175
00:11:44,240 --> 00:11:45,036
<i>Xavier!</i>

176
00:11:45,400 --> 00:11:46,674
Hold on. Not you, mom.

177
00:11:47,560 --> 00:11:48,356
Give me...

178
00:11:50,080 --> 00:11:50,956
The code.

179
00:11:51,320 --> 00:11:53,914
<i>My new door code is 20B 10.</i>

180
00:11:56,000 --> 00:11:57,592
Okay, I've really gotta go...

181
00:11:58,400 --> 00:12:00,311
Mom, hold on!

182
00:12:01,200 --> 00:12:03,111
- Hi, Mrs. Lopez.
- You have to pick up your mail.

183
00:12:03,480 --> 00:12:05,516
It's been piling up for a week.

184
00:12:06,320 --> 00:12:08,151
Can I borrow a DVD?

185
00:12:08,480 --> 00:12:09,879
You done yet?

186
00:12:10,240 --> 00:12:14,597
I caught you off guard the other day,
and now I'm a little off guard...

187
00:12:14,960 --> 00:12:15,756
Coming, mom.

188
00:12:19,400 --> 00:12:20,389
I'll stop back later.

189
00:12:23,480 --> 00:12:25,550
All clear? Can I talk now?

190
00:12:25,920 --> 00:12:26,955
<i>Is it my turn?</i>

191
00:12:27,320 --> 00:12:29,356
<i>You've got grampa tonight.</i>

192
00:12:29,720 --> 00:12:30,391
I'll be there!

193
00:12:31,000 --> 00:12:32,956
<i>My neighbor, Mr. Boubaker,</i>

194
00:12:33,280 --> 00:12:35,953
<i>is the most uninteresting guy on earth.</i>

195
00:12:36,320 --> 00:12:37,275
Hey...

196
00:12:37,920 --> 00:12:38,875
You know what?

197
00:12:39,240 --> 00:12:40,912
The Big Bang theory doesn't work.

198
00:12:41,280 --> 00:12:45,353
They said on the radio this morning
it may not be true.

199
00:12:45,720 --> 00:12:47,278
Well, no one knows for sure.

200
00:12:47,640 --> 00:12:48,629
<i>If he only knew.</i>

201
00:12:49,000 --> 00:12:51,719
<i>When I write a story,</i>
<i>I always think of Mr. Boubaker.</i>

202
00:12:52,080 --> 00:12:55,550
<i>I try to imagine the scene</i>
<i>with "Mr. Average Guy."</i>

203
00:12:57,480 --> 00:12:59,471
<i>That's him! "Mr. Average Guy."</i>

204
00:12:59,840 --> 00:13:03,389
<i>It's rare to meet one.</i>
<i>There aren't that many in real life.</i>

205
00:13:03,760 --> 00:13:05,432
- Are you expecting anyone?
- No.

206
00:13:06,360 --> 00:13:08,078
- But who can it be?
- I don't know.

207
00:13:11,200 --> 00:13:13,395
Oh, Barbara, what does this mean?

208
00:13:13,760 --> 00:13:15,432
I thought I'd find you here.

209
00:13:17,520 --> 00:13:18,589
So, she's the one.

210
00:13:19,920 --> 00:13:20,955
You disappoint me.

211
00:13:22,080 --> 00:13:23,718
I thought she'd at least be...

212
00:13:24,280 --> 00:13:25,235
She'd be what?

213
00:13:25,600 --> 00:13:27,238
Yeah, she'd be what?

214
00:13:48,200 --> 00:13:49,110
Excuse me.

215
00:13:49,920 --> 00:13:51,239
What's your girlfriend like?

216
00:13:51,600 --> 00:13:53,238
It's not for my girlfriend.

217
00:13:54,680 --> 00:13:56,033
I don't have a girlfriend.

218
00:13:56,400 --> 00:13:59,073
What's this girl
who's not your girlfriend like?

219
00:14:00,480 --> 00:14:02,311
She's a little shorter than you.

220
00:14:02,680 --> 00:14:04,796
She has smaller... I mean...

221
00:14:05,360 --> 00:14:07,316
I think she's size one or two.

222
00:14:07,680 --> 00:14:09,910
It depends. Is she thinner than I am?

223
00:14:10,920 --> 00:14:12,148
Is she like that girl?

224
00:14:14,560 --> 00:14:15,197
No.

225
00:14:18,640 --> 00:14:20,596
She's more like her.

226
00:14:21,280 --> 00:14:22,508
But not as ugly.

227
00:14:24,280 --> 00:14:25,554
Take the two.

228
00:14:26,240 --> 00:14:29,152
Your girlfriend can always exchange it.

229
00:14:31,640 --> 00:14:33,073
The register's over there.

230
00:14:33,440 --> 00:14:36,910
<i>By the way,</i>
<i>I've been a bachelor for a year.</i>

231
00:14:37,440 --> 00:14:38,634
I love your hair.

232
00:14:42,640 --> 00:14:43,959
I prefer that you leave.

233
00:14:45,040 --> 00:14:45,950
Really?

234
00:14:47,920 --> 00:14:49,114
I'm sorry, I'm very modest.

235
00:14:49,840 --> 00:14:51,159
Look, I've gotta run.

236
00:14:52,000 --> 00:14:53,513
Okay, I'm going!

237
00:14:53,880 --> 00:14:55,916
I wasn't chasing you out.

238
00:14:56,280 --> 00:14:58,874
Don't sweat it. I'm outta here!

239
00:14:59,680 --> 00:15:02,399
That was great. I had a blast.
Thanks a lot.

240
00:15:03,480 --> 00:15:05,038
Why are you talking like that?

241
00:15:05,440 --> 00:15:07,351
Because I'm a big jerk.

242
00:15:08,040 --> 00:15:09,109
<i>So...</i>

243
00:15:10,120 --> 00:15:12,236
<i>I just wanted to say</i>
<i>I'm a bachelor...</i>

244
00:15:17,920 --> 00:15:18,557
Bye.

245
00:15:25,560 --> 00:15:29,394
Not to be too insistent...
this really isn't for my girlfriend.

246
00:15:31,640 --> 00:15:33,278
It's no biggie. Who cares?

247
00:15:33,640 --> 00:15:35,710
I don't have a girlfriend.

